```src/css/Style.css
/* src/BlogPosts/Style.css */
body {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 20px;
    font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    transition: background-color 0.3s, color 0.3s;
    --bg-color: #ffffff;
    /* Default light theme */
    --text-color: #000000;
}

.container {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 20px;
    background-color: var(--bg-color);
    color: var(--text-color);
    border-radius: 8px;
}

/* Light theme (optional, overrides default) */
body.light-theme {
    --bg-color: #ffffff;
    --text-color: #000000;
}

/* Dark theme */
body.dark-theme {
    --bg-color: #121212;
    --text-color: #ffffff;
}

/* Section styling with visual distinction */
section {
    margin-bottom: 40px;
    padding: 15px;
    background-color: rgba(128, 128, 128, 0.1);
    border-left: 4px solid #333;
}

/* Theme toggle button styling */
.theme-button {
    position: fixed;
    top: 20px;
    right: 20px;
    padding: 10px 16px;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 4px;
    cursor: pointer;
    z-index: 1000;
}

.theme-button:hover {
    background-color: #555;
}

/* Responsive design */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
    .container {
        padding: 10px;
    }

    section {
        padding: 10px;
        font-size: 14px;
    }
}


section {
    padding: 10px;
    font-size: 14px;

    /* Light theme (optional, overrides default) */
    body.light-theme {
        --bg-color: #ffffff;
        --text-color: #000000;
    }
}
```

message.content:
The issue with the theme toggle not applying the styles is due to two main problems:

1. **Missing `.container` wrapper**: The `.container` class in your CSS is responsible for applying the theme colors via CSS variables (`--bg-color` and `--text-color`). However, the content (e.g., `<h1>`, `<div>`) is not wrapped in an element with the `.container` class. As a result, the background/text color changes defined in `.container` are never applied.

2. **Incorrect CSS structure**: The CSS has a nested `body.light-theme` rule inside the `section` selector, which is invalid. This doesn't affect the current issue but should be fixed for clarity.

---

### ✅ Fix 1: Wrap content in `.container` (HTML)
Update your `index.html` to wrap the content inside a `.container` div:

```html
<!-- index.html -->
<body class="light-theme">
    <button class="theme-button">Toggle Theme</button>
    <script src="./src/js/theme-toggle.js"></script>

    <div class="container">
        <h1>Midiestro Posts</h1>
        <div>
            <p>...</p>
            <ul>...</ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</body>
```

---

### ✅ Fix 2: Remove invalid nested CSS (Style.css)
Fix the nested `body.light-theme` inside the `section` selector by moving it to its own rule. This is optional but improves clarity:

```css
/* src/css/Style.css */
section {
    padding: 10px;
    font-size: 14px;
}

/* Move this rule outside the `section` block */
body.light-theme section {
    --bg-color: #ffffff;
    --text-color: #000000;
}
```

---

### ✅ Optional: Improve toggle logic (theme-toggle.js)
Currently, the code toggles both classes on the same button click. This could lead to unexpected behavior if misused. A better approach is to check the current class and toggle accordingly:

```javascript
// src/js/theme-toggle.js
const themeButton = document.querySelector('.theme-button');

themeButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
  if (document.body.classList.contains('light-theme')) {
    document.body.classList.remove('light-theme');
    document.body.classList.add('dark-theme');
  } else {
    document.body.classList.remove('dark-theme');
    document.body.classList.add('light-theme');
  }
});
```

---

### Summary
- Wrap your content in a `<div class="container">` to ensure the theme colors (via CSS variables) are applied.
- Fix invalid CSS structure to avoid confusion.
- Optionally refine the toggle logic to make it more robust.

After these changes, clicking the "Toggle Theme" button should now correctly switch the background and text colors as defined in your `.container` styles.

